{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568653"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:20:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21285"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21285"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.05,0.24,0.04,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14158"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106713"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14158"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21285"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89193"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"480"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"2328"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34325"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34326"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34661"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39464"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43955"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106713"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the pre-admissions unit for an upcoming colonoscopy after a positive faecal occult blood test as part of the national bowel cancer screening programme. He has been otherwise asymptomatic. His medical history includes ischaemic heart disease with previous percutaneous coronary intervention ten years ago, dyslipidaemia, hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and knee osteoarthritis. His regular medications are aspirin, candesartan, rosuvastatin, metoprolol, metformin extended release, empagliflozin, and paracetamol extended release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate approach to medication management preoperatively?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Withhold empagliflozin 3 days prior to procedure","Withhold metformin 3 days prior to procedure","Withhold aspirin 7 days prior to procedure","Withhold metoprolol morning of procedure","No medication alterations are required"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithhold empagliflozin 3 days prior to procedure\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Euglycaemic diabetic ketoacidosis is a recognised complication of sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 inhibitor therapy, particularly in the context of physiological stress, fasting, or reduced carbohydrate intake, such as during bowel preparation for colonoscopy. Withholding these agents for at least three days prior to the procedure, as recommended by Australian guidelines, significantly reduces this risk. Euglycaemic diabetic ketoacidosis can present with normal or only mildly elevated blood glucose, making it more difficult to recognise and potentially life-threatening if not anticipated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithhold metformin 3 days prior to procedure\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Metformin should be withheld usually the day before and day of colonoscopy whilst the patient is on a clear fluid diet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithhold aspirin 7 days prior to procedure\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Aspirin should generally be continued for colonoscopy given the risk of thrombosis if withheld, although this is at the discretion of the proceduralist and in certain scenarios with high bleeding risk, may be withheld.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithhold metoprolol morning of procedure\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Generally, metoprolol can be safely continued prior to colonoscopy to suppress tachycardia and hypertension associated with anaesthesia. Should the metoprolol need to be ceased prior to colonoscopy for another reason, there should be a gradual reduction due to the risk of rebound tachycardia upon rapid cessation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo medication alterations are required\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Empagliflozin should be discontinued 3 days prior, metformin 1 day prior whilst on clear fluid diet, but all other medications can usually be safely continued.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 inhibitors should be withheld for at least three days prior to procedures involving fasting or bowel preparation to reduce the risk of euglycaemic diabetic ketoacidosis.","Euglycaemic diabetic ketoacidosis can occur even with normal or mildly elevated blood glucose, especially during periods of physiological stress or reduced carbohydrate intake.","Withholding sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 inhibitors does not significantly reduce the risk of hypoglycaemia or urogenital infections in the peri-procedural period."],"references":["Clinical Excellence Commission. Guidelines on perioperative management of anticoagulant and antiplatelet agents [Internet]. 2025. Available from: https://www.cec.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0006/458988/Guidelines-on-perioperative-management-of-anticoagulant-and-antiplatelet-agents.pdf","Australian Diabetes Society; Australian and New Zealand College of Anaesthetists \u0026 Faculty of Pain Medicine Peri\u2011operative Diabetes Working Party. ADS\u2011ANZCA Perioperative Diabetes and Hyperglycaemia Guidelines (Adults) [Internet]. Melbourne (AU): Australian Diabetes Society\u202f\u0026\u202fANZCA; Nov\u00a014\u00a02022 [cited 2025 Jun\u00a022]. Available from: https://www.diabetessociety.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/ADS-ANZCA-Perioperative-Diabetes-and-Hyperglycaemia-Guidelines-Adults-November-2022-v2-Final.pdf","Medicines Advice Initiative Australia. Perioperative management of SGLT2 inhibitors and GLP-1 receptor agonists CATAG Practice Tool [Internet]. 2024 [cited 2025 Apr 21]. Available from: https://catag.org.au/wp-content/uploads/CATAG-Topic_Diabetes_Practice-Tool_F.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89193"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21285"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89193"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-22T09:58:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-22T09:59:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14158"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106713"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}